# Coaching App — Cursor Rules

## Project overview
This is a coaching and athlete management platform for coaches and personal trainers.
It allows coaches to manage clients, plan workouts, track progress, and manage team calendars.

## Tech stack
- Monorepo using Yarn workspaces and Turborepo
- apps/next — Next.js 16 web app (App Router)
- apps/expo — Expo (React Native) mobile app for iOS and Android
- packages/app — shared screens, navigation, and business logic
- packages/ui — shared UI components (planned; web UI currently lives in apps/next/components/)
- Supabase for database, authentication, and storage (PostgreSQL)
- NativeWind / Tailwind CSS for styling
- TypeScript throughout

## Project structure rules
- Shared screens and logic go in packages/app/features
- Shared components go in packages/ui (when created); web-only UI in apps/next/components/
- Web-only pages go in apps/next/app
- Mobile-only screens go in apps/expo
- Supabase SSR clients live in apps/next/lib/supabase/ (server.ts, middleware.ts)
- Environment variables are prefixed with NEXT_PUBLIC_

## Code style
- Always use TypeScript, never plain JavaScript
- Use async/await, never .then() chains
- Use named exports, not default exports for components
- Use Tailwind/NativeWind for all styling, no inline styles
- Keep components small and single-purpose

## Database
- Database is PostgreSQL via Supabase
- All tables have created_at and updated_at timestamps
- Use row-level security (RLS) on all tables
- Key tables: coaches, clients, teams, workout_plans, scheduled_sessions, workout_logs

## When generating code
- Always consider both web (Next.js) and mobile (React Native) when building shared components
- Use Solito for navigation between web and mobile
- Prefer server components in Next.js unless interactivity is needed
- Always handle loading and error states
- Always validate user input